<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Salmon Preparation</strong> - The cooking method dramatically affects your wine choice. Grilled or blackened salmon with its Maillard reaction compounds pairs beautifully with medium-bodied Pinot Noirs from cooler climates like Oregon's Willamette Valley, while delicate poached salmon calls for lighter wines like Sancerre or Grüner Veltliner. The char and caramelization create savory notes that need wines with enough tannin structure to complement, not compete.</li>

  <li><strong>Leverage Salmon's Natural Oils for Texture Pairing</strong> - Salmon's high omega-3 content creates a rich, buttery mouthfeel that pairs exceptionally with wines offering complementary textures. Burgundian Chardonnay aged on lees provides creamy texture that mirrors the fish's richness, while the wine's natural acidity cuts through the oils. For red wine lovers, choose Pinot Noirs with silky tannins rather than grippy ones—think Carneros over Barolo.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Whites at Cellar Temperature, Not Refrigerator Cold</strong> - For salmon pairings, serve white wines at 50-55°F rather than the typical 40-45°F. This slightly warmer temperature allows the wine's aromatics to open up and match salmon's robust flavor profile. Chilled wines can taste thin against salmon's richness, while cellar temperature brings out the wine's texture and complexity needed to stand up to this meaty fish.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Whites, Quick Aerate Young Reds</strong> - White wines paired with salmon should go straight from bottle to glass to preserve their fresh acidity and delicate aromatics. For red wines, young Oregon or Burgundy Pinot Noirs benefit from 15-20 minutes of breathing in a decanter to soften any aggressive tannins that could clash with salmon's delicate texture. Avoid over-aerating—salmon requires wine finesse, not bold, oxidized flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Bowls for Both Reds and Whites</strong> - The wide bowl of a Burgundy glass concentrates both the earthy, mushroom notes in Pinot Noir and the mineral complexity in white Burgundy—both essential elements that complement salmon's umami richness. The tapered rim directs these subtle aromatics to your nose, enhancing the pairing. Avoid narrow flutes or small glasses that compress the wine's expression.</li>

  <li><strong>Prioritize Young to Medium-Aged Wines</strong> - Salmon pairs best with wines that retain bright fruit and fresh acidity rather than heavily aged bottles. For whites, choose wines under 3-5 years old to maintain the crisp minerality that cuts through salmon's oils. For reds, opt for Pinot Noirs aged 2-8 years—old enough for tannin integration but young enough to retain the cherry and raspberry fruit notes that complement salmon's sweetness.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Service with Salmon's Temperature</strong> - Serve your wine when salmon reaches room temperature if serving cold preparations like gravlax, or immediately alongside hot preparations. The contrast between warm salmon and properly chilled white wine creates a palate-cleansing effect, while room-temperature salmon with slightly cool red wine (60-62°F) creates seamless flavor integration.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Salmon Species for Wine Style Selection</strong> - Atlantic salmon's milder, more delicate flavor pairs beautifully with elegant wines like Chablis or light Pinot Grigio, while robust King salmon can handle more powerful wines like Russian River Chardonnay or Willamette Valley Pinot Noir. Sockeye salmon's pronounced flavor and firm texture demands wines with matching intensity—think Sancerre Rouge or Côte de Beaune Pinot Noir with its mineral backbone and structured tannins.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with grilled versus poached salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops char and caramelization that pairs beautifully with fuller-bodied wines like oaked Chardonnay or light Pinot Noir, while poached salmon's delicate texture calls for crisp, mineral-driven whites like Sancerre or Albariño. The cooking method significantly impacts the salmon's flavor intensity—grilled fish can handle wines with more tannins and oak, whereas poached preparations need wines that won't overpower the subtle fish flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve salmon wine pairings at the same temperature?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines should be served chilled at 45-50°F, while light reds like Pinot Noir work best slightly cooler than room temperature at 55-60°F. Serve the salmon warm (around 145°F internal temperature) to create the ideal contrast between the cool wine and warm fish. This temperature difference enhances both the wine's refreshing qualities and the salmon's rich, buttery flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing overly heavy, tannic red wines that clash with salmon's delicate oils and can create a metallic taste. Many people default to bold Cabernet Sauvignon or Malbec, which overwhelm the fish's subtle flavors. Instead, focus on wines with bright acidity and moderate body—the acidity cuts through the salmon's richness while complementing rather than competing with its flavor.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair the same wine with both Atlantic and Pacific salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While both work with similar wine styles, Atlantic salmon's higher fat content and milder flavor pairs better with richer whites like oaked Chardonnay or Viognier. Pacific salmon varieties like Coho or Chinook have more pronounced flavors that can handle slightly bolder wines, including light-bodied reds. Consider the specific salmon variety and its oil content when making your selection for the most harmonious pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is salmon wine pairing good for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Salmon is an excellent choice for wine pairing beginners because it's forgiving and works with a wide range of wines, from crisp Sauvignon Blanc to elegant Pinot Noir. The fish's moderate flavor intensity won't clash dramatically with most wine choices, making it easier to experiment and learn. Start with classic pairings like Chardonnay or Rosé, then explore as your palate develops confidence.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good budget-friendly alternatives to expensive salmon wine pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Instead of pricey Burgundian Chardonnay, try excellent value options like Washington State Chardonnay or Spanish Albariño, both offering similar mineral complexity and acidity. For red wine lovers, swap expensive Oregon Pinot Noir for Loire Valley Chinon or Beaujolais-Villages, which provide the same light-bodied, food-friendly character. These alternatives often cost half the price while delivering comparable pairing success with salmon dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does salmon preparation sauce affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rich sauces like hollandaise or cream-based preparations call for wines with higher acidity and more body, such as oaked Chardonnay or white Rhône blends. Citrus-based sauces pair beautifully with crisp wines like Vermentino or Grüner Veltliner, while herb crusts or pesto work well with herbaceous wines like Sancerre. Always consider the sauce as much as the fish itself—it often becomes the dominant flavor that drives your wine selection.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I use leftover salmon wine pairing bottles for other seafood dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—wines that pair well with salmon are versatile choices for most seafood preparations. Crisp whites like Chablis or Pinot Grigio work excellently with shellfish, while the light reds suitable for salmon also complement tuna or swordfish. Store opened bottles properly with a wine preserver or in the refrigerator, and use within 2-3 days for optimal flavor when preparing your next seafood meal.</p>
